that took place in Japanese party politics during the postwar period. This study advances an alternative set of interpretations based on a microanalytic approach that highlights the incentive and bargaining power of individual political actors, and their competitive and strategic behavior under existing institutional constraints. According to Kohno, the evolution of political life in postwar Japan depends on the same factors that are acknowledged to be at work in other industrialized nations. He reveals, through detailed case studies of government formation processes and statistical examinations of candidate nomination patterns, that the microanalytic approach can establish forward-looking and internally consistent interpretations of the postwar development of Japanese party politics. Because Japan has usually been treated as a country of unique cultural, historical, and societal characteristics, the analyses of this study point to the broader applicability of the microanalytic approach in the field of comparative politics, especially for the exploration of party competition in advanced industrial democracies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAmerican Occupation.  aAshida, Hitoshi.  aAudience cost.  aConfucianism.  aConstitution.  aDemocratic Socialist Party (DSP).  aDodge Economic Plan.  aElectoral reform.  aGHQ (General Headquarters).  aHata, Tsutomu.  aHosokawa, Morihiro.  aIkeda, Hayato.  aInukai, Ken.  aIshii, Mitsujiro.  aJapan New Party (JNP).  aJapan Socialist Party (JSP).  aKatayama, Tetsu.  aKishi, Nobusuke.  aLabor movement.  aLifetime employment system.  aMiki, Bukichi.  aNational Cooperativist Party.  aNishio, Suehiro.  aOgata, Taketora.  aOzawa, Ichiro.  aPostwar reform.  aSakigake.  aTakemura, Masayoshi